Jacklin here, as the format wars wage on. I think I've picked a side. I pledge my eternal loyalty to Ghostbin and will serve as their autismo general in the coming conflict.
Ghostbin is basically pastebin with a darkmode I don't have to pay for. The pastes don't expire and it supports a number of coding languages in you're into that sort of thing. I'm already talked about my issues with SF, but my issue with AO3 besides the ambiguity around the original content is that it is simply exposing me to a wider audience.
I don't want a wider audience, I don't want to be a part of the "AO3 community" when I write stories for this general, I want it to be only for this general. Then throw in the stuff I've heard about underage stuff getting posted on there and it seems that ghostbin is a simple upgrade.

You can make an account on the site and keep track of your pastes. The only downside is that you can't easily showcase the list of your pastes by clicking on your username or whatever like you can with pastebin. Even then you can just make a separate paste with the links to all of your work.

I have only put up one on my stories: Underneath the Armor.
https://ghostbin.co/paste/hnc2k
This is like a three year old story but I still like it. Also I'm going to be working on a sequel for it so it felt appropriate to put it up first. I'll be uploading the rest of my work on ghostbin in the future. I will also be deleting my pastebin and all the work associated with it. I don't want to show an ounce of support for that site. I feel really bad for the people who paid for the premium accounts and now are getting fucked over.

Jacklin again, back with another update on all this shit.
I found a way to wrap text on ghostbin, though it's not perfect. You have to change the language setting on the upper right corner from "plain text" to "markdown" and that will initiate a text wrap when you save the file.
However this comes with its own set of problems. If you use greentext everything is going to bundle together into big clumps of texts. In order to avoid this you have to take this:
>Anon pet the fuzzy waifur
>She is very soft
And do this:
>Anon pet the fuzzy Waifur

>She is very soft

That means if you're like me and wrote a 50k+ story that you're copying and pasting, you need to manually go in a put a space between every.single.line. I am in the process of doing this just to see how it looks in the end. I don't think I will do it again.
Another issue is that Markdown doesn't actually pickup the greentext arrow. So it'll look like this:
Greentext
instead of this:
>Greentext

There are reasons why this may be an issue. But honestly I'm not in the mood to talk in length about the technical of literary greentext.
I'll probably go on AO3 once I get my invite, I should be getting it tomorrow. I think a mixed approach for formats will probably be the best thing and the OP will probably be awashed with story links from SF, AO3, and whatever bin people prefer. I think that's for the best.
